Principal Component Analysis

PCA- A unsupervised feature extraction algorithm that aims to maximize the variance along the extracted features

Why maximize variance?

In [1]:
each=200
Ca<-cbind(rnorm(each,mean=5,sd=1.15),rnorm(200,mean=4,sd=1.05))
Cb<-cbind(rnorm(each,mean=14,sd=1.15),rnorm(200,mean=7,sd=1.05))
X<-rbind(Ca,Cb)
cat(" Glimpse of Dataset X: \n")
print(X[1:5,])

pchs= c(22,24)[true]
plot(X,col="black",bg=colvec,pch=pchs,xlab="Feature1",ylab="Feature2",main="Scatter plot of Data")

Variance gives a notion of the structure of the data

PCA Objective Find direction 1v1 a linear combination of Feature 1 and Feature 2 that maximizes the variance of the projected data

Projected data:

=1(1)(1)y=Xv1

Say 1=[1112]v1=[v11v12], the projected data =y=Xv implies

=11Feature 1+11Feature 2(2)(2)y=v11Feature 1+v11Feature 2

y is a linear combination of Feature 1 and Feature 2.

maximize()=1(1)=11(3)(3)maximizevar(y)=1(n1)yTy=v1TXTXv1

For mean-centered data X:

1(1)1(n1)XTX is the Covariance matrix of X

maximize11subject to11=1,(4)(4)maximizev1TCv1subject tov1Tv1=1,

where =1(1)C=1(n1)XTX and 1v1 is unit vector as only the direction of maximum variance matters.

Solution for 1v1 in (4)(4) given by the eigenvector of C corresponding largest eigenvalue.

Principal components of X : Project X on the eigenvectors of its covaraince matrix C
